<title>CHILD SUPPORT ENFORCEMENT: QUESTIONS AND CAVEATS</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/infocus/infocus.gif">

<p>

<h2>CHILD SUPPORT ENFORCEMENT:<br>
QUESTIONS AND CAVEATS</h2></center>

<hr size = 3 width = 50%>

<p>

<li><b>Can we expect child support enforcement legislation to
increase child support payments substantially?</b>

<p>

A 1992 General Accounting Office report found that 14 percent
of fathers who owe child support are dead and that 66 percent
&quot;cannot afford to pay the amount ordered&quot; because they
are not employed by legal activity.  Many of these delinquent
fathers are addicts, alcoholics, mental patients, or prison inmates.

<p>

On the other hand, Bill Harrington of the American Fathers' Coalition
reports that only between 5 percent and 10 percent of fathers
are &quot;deadbeats&quot; in the conventional sense, meaning that
they &quot;don't give one penny of support or one minute of their
time.&quot;

<p>

<li><b>Will draconian child support enforcement serve the best
interest of mothers and children?</b>

<p>

In 1989, after passage of the Family Support Act of 1988, about
20 percent of unwed mothers without support awards said that they
did not want awards and another 21 percent did not pursue an award.

<p>

A group of former welfare mothers explained to a reporter (<I>The
New York Times</I>, February 17, 1995) that &quot;they know better
than anybody what will happen if . . . the Government makes fugitives
of men who the women say do not have jobs or money to pay the
child support.  They say it is the children who will suffer for
this, that the men will come after the women and blame or beat
them for the punitive actions of the state.&quot;

<p>

The women in the interview concluded, &quot;The whole [welfare]
system is anti-family, first by keeping the father from the home
and then by pitting mother against father over child support poor
men usually cannot pay. . . .  'My son needs a relationship with
his father,' [one mother] said.  'That has no cash value.'&quot;

<p>

Restoring the fathers' physical presence in children's lives is
in fact the most reliable means of guaranteeing child support.
When fathers do receive visitation, almost 80 percent pay full
child support, on time.  When fathers receive joint custody, the
child support compliance rate exceeds 90 percent.  In studying
the National Longitudinal Surveys of Labor Market Experience, Youth
Cohort (NLSY) data set, economist Robert Lerman found that unwed
fathers who rarely or never visited their children were also the ones 
least likely to pay child support.  Those who later married were 
suddenly motivated to increase their earnings dramatically, even 
without additional job training, according to Lerman.

<p>

<li><b>What is the proper balance between fathers' rights and
responsibilities?</b>

<p>

Under current law, a father's legal rights may be heavily circumscribed
or completely thwarted by the mother's noncooperation.  One study
found that almost half of all mothers interfere even when the
father has won visitation rights.

<p>

Economist and social critic George Gilder describes both the danger
and the futility of increasing welfare mothers' independence at
the expense of fathers' rights.  &quot;Nothing is so futile,&quot;
he writes, &quot;as efforts to force men to support for life a
child they 'father' out of wedlock while abortion laws deny them
any power to determine whether the child is born and while the
welfare regime denies them any economic power to marry the mother.&quot;
The attendant frustration, Gilder warns, increases men's propensity
for violence.

<p>

If unwed fathers are to be legally obligated to pay child support
to women who are on welfare, it seems neither sensible nor equitable
to deny fathers access to the same job training and employment
opportunity programs to which mothers are entitled.

<p>

<li><b>Should the IRS be responsible for enforcing payment of
child support?</b>

<p>

Shifting the responsibility for child support enforcement to the
IRS raises the danger that failure to collect checks from delinquent
fathers will very easily evolve into remitting government checks
instead -- a proposal which has been floated in Congress in the
past.  Enforcement by the IRS is only one small step removed from
exchanging &quot;personal responsibility&quot; for new social
responsibility and from exalting government in place of family.

<p>

<li><b>What principles should be embodied in a positive alternative?</b>

<p>

The problem inherent in child support enforcement is, as social
scientist Charles Murray has said, that &quot;it is next to impossible
for anyone, including the state, to force a man to take on the
responsibilities of fatherhood.&quot;  The best child support
is an intact marriage, and policymakers should seriously consider
restoring the distinctiveness of marriage by making it once again
the sole legal institution through which parental rights and responsibilities
are defined and exercised.

<p>

Experts estimate that 30 to 40 percent of low-income men living
apart from their families still maintain a relationship with them
and that a large percentage of delinquent fathers fail to contribute
child support simply because they have no income.  We should consider
allowing fathers to satisfy the welfare reform work requirements
while mothers care for the children -- a measure that could increase
&quot;child support&quot; by rebuilding spousal interdependence.

<p>

<center>
<b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/infocus/">Other In Focus</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/policypapers.html">Other Policy Papers</a>]
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/reproduce/reproduc.html">Reproducing This 
Article</a>]
</b>

<p>
<hr size = 3>
<p>

