<html>

<title>JUVENILE VIOLENCE INCREASING</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>JUVENILE VIOLENCE<br>
INCREASING</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Robert L. Maginnis</i></center>

<p>

Murder rates may be down, but not among adolescents, according
to a recent Justice Department report.  Since 1965, there has
been a 467 percent increase in the murder arrest rate for 18-year-olds.
The future murder trends suggest ever-younger offenders.  Something
must be done.
<p>
On a typical day in 1994, nine teenagers in the U.S. were murdered
and 13 teenagers committed a murder, the report said.  According
to Attorney General Janet Reno, the problem of children killing
is likely to worsen because demographics show that the key at-risk
population -- 14- to 17-year-olds -- will increase significantly
in years to come.
<p>
In 10 years there will be 23 percent more teenagers and, given
current trends, murder could increase to 40,000 killings per year
 -- that's a 67 percent rise!   James Q. Wilson, co-editor of
the book <I>Crime</I>, said, &quot;So we should expect, unless
something changes dramatically, that the [now lower] crime rate
will go back up.&quot;
<p>
While social scientists cannot show definite cause-and-effect
relationships for murder,  they can demonstrate that certain conditions
highly correlate with the increase in juvenile violence.  For
example, parental absence increases a child's likelihood of future
criminal behavior.
<p>
A 1990 study by June O'Neill, a professor with Baruch College
of the City University of New York, shows that men from single-parent
families are twice as likely to commit crimes as men from two-parent
families. Robert Sampson, professor of sociology at the University of 
Chicago, notes that it is harder for single-parent families to achieve
the &quot;informal social controls&quot; that limit both crime
and victimization.  &quot;There are higher crime rates in places
where communities are not characterized by strong families,&quot;
he said.
<p>
Even children from two-parent homes suffer when both parents are
absent most of the day due to outside jobs.  A Justice Department
study concluded that parental supervision, attachment to family,
and consistency of discipline were the most important barriers
to delinquency and drug abuse.
<p>
Likewise, drug abuse which directly correlates with delinquent
behavior, is on the rise among adolescents.  Andrew Peyton Thomas,
Arizona assistant attorney general and former NAACP counsel, writes
in <I>Crime and the Sacking of America</I>, &quot;There is...an
undeniable relationship between crime and drugs.  Drug addiction
can both lower inhibitions among offenders and spur them on to
other crimes to finance their dependency.&quot;
<p>
A 1993 Justice Department study of 4,000 urban youths over a five-year
period identified a pattern leading to delinquency.  The study
found a direct connection between drug use and delinquent behavior.
<p>
Finally, most Americans blame pop culture as a third reason for
increases in youth violence.  According to the Family Research
Council's 1995 nationwide poll (conducted by Voter/Consumer Research),
more than nine of every 10 Americans believe the media affects
violent crime to some extent.
<p>
Robert McAffee, president of the American Medical Association,
agrees.  He said, &quot;If you combine television, motion pictures,
rap music and video games, there's a continuing influence of 
violence....[and] violence is indeed a learned behavior.&quot;
<p>
By age 18, the average child watches 100,000 acts of television
violence, according to Robert Butterworth, a Los Angeles-based
child psychologist.  Before the end of elementary school, the
average child witnesses 8,000 television murders, Butterworth
adds.  This much violence has an undeniable affect.
<p>
According to an analysis of 275 studies, George Comstock, a professor
at Syracuse University, says that perhaps 10 percent of antisocial
and illegal acts can be linked to television.
<p>
Epidemiologist Brandon S. Centerwall told <I>Newsweek</I> last
December that without television there would be 10,000 fewer murders
per year, 70,000 fewer rapes and 700,000 fewer assaults.
<p>
The music industry also shares some of the responsibility.  Dr.
Joseph Stuessey, professor of music history at the University
of Texas, told the U.S. Senate Commerce Committee, &quot;Music
affects behavior.  This simple fact has been known intuitively
for centuries.&quot;
<p>
Pop culture's music is laden with violence.  It has themes of
murder, maiming, raping, abusing and destroying.  Rap and heavy
metal are the worst, but others contribute to the promotion of
violence.
<p>
Dr. Sheila Davis, a professor of lyrics at New York University,
says songs &quot;are a potent force in the shaping of&quot; society.
&quot;Popular songs,&quot; she says, &quot;provide the primary
'equipment for living' for America's youth.&quot; No wonder
youth violence is rising.
<p>
Americans perceive that crime is getting worse.  Although overall
crime rates may be down, the face of crime is changing.  Citizens
feel less safe.  There's no quick fix, but strengthening the family,
boosting juvenile courts, stopping gratuitous media violence and
fighting drugs will help.

<p>
-- 2/7/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<I>Robert Maginnis is a senior policy analyst with the Family
Research Council, a Washington, D.C.-based research and advocacy
organization.</I>

<p>

