<title>LEAVING THE VULNERABLE OPEN TO ABUSE</title>

<body>

<center><img src="/townhall/FRC/perspective/perspective.gif">

<p>

<h2>LEAVING THE VULNERABLE<br>
OPEN TO ABUSE</h2>

<p><hr size=3 width=50%><p>

<i>by</i>

<p>

<i>Gracie S. Hsu</i></center>

<p>

It used to be that the man in every girl's life was her father.
He was her protector and provider, shielding her honor and ensuring
her safety.

<p>

But today, with the rise in illegitimacy and divorce, fewer fathers
are around to protect and defend their daughters' safety and honor.
With more girls lacking the love and attention that only a father
can give, more of them are willing to settle for perverse alternatives,
namely, seeking intimacy with predatory adult men.

<p>

Numerous studies, such as the U.S. Department of Health and Human
Services' <I>National Health Interview Survey</I> (1988), have
found that children from disrupted families are at a much higher
risk for physical or sexual abuse than children from intact, two-parent
families.  Furthermore, children whose parents separate are significantly
more likely to engage in early sexual activity than their peers
from intact, two-parent families, according to a 1994 study in
<I>Journal of the American Academy of Child and Adolescent Psychiatry</I>.
But the latest statistics are even more shocking.

<p>

For example, a recent study by the Population Reference Bureau
found that about two-thirds of births to teenage girls nationwide
are fathered by adult men age 20 or older.

<p>

State health figures in Massachusetts confirm this finding.  In
1993 (the latest data available), more than half of the state's
teen pregnancies were sired by adult men.  Almost 60 percent of
the fathers in 3,663 births to teen moms were men aged 20-29,
and another 139 births resulted from teen girls having sex with
men aged 30 and older.

<p>

Likewise, a review of California's 1990 vital statistics found
that men older than high school age accounted for 77 percent of
all births among high school-aged girls (ages 16-18) and for 51 percent 
of births among junior high school-aged girls (15 and younger).  Men over
age 25 fathered twice as many teenage births as did boys under
age 18, while senior high school boys fathered only 24 percent
of births among all teenage girls.

<p>

Additionally, the Alan Guttmacher Institute's 1994 report, &quot;Sex
and America's Teenagers,&quot; found that six of 10 girls who
had sex before age 15 were coerced by males an average of six
years their senior.

<p>

Fatherlessness, however, not only creates the environment for
more vulnerable girls, it also helps create more predatory males.
Research clearly shows that boys who grow up without fathers
are far more likely to engage in violent behavior and promiscuity
than those who grow up in two-parent homes.  Indeed, according
to a 1990 article by Nicholas Davidson in <I>Policy Review</I>,
60 percent of America's rapists grew up in homes without fathers.

<p>

While absent fathers figure prominently in this new phenomenon
of child abuse, they are not solely to blame for the devastation.
The &quot;village&quot; has also failed in its responsibility
to protect children.  For example, television and movies regularly
expose children to sexually explicit images, glamorizing sex and
violence.

<p>

Lax enforcement of statutory rape laws has also added fuel to
the fire.  Although renewed efforts to prosecute and punish statutory
rapists, such as those undertaken by California governor Pete
Wilson, are needed and ought to be encouraged, a law enforcement
strategy alone cannot stem the tide.  Prevention must be emphasized.

<p>

Some have proposed that the way to &quot;prevent&quot; this problem
is to expose children at progressively younger and younger ages
to more explicit sex education in the school, so that children
can learn how to protect themselves with condoms, etc.  But this
scenario is a textbook case in which the &quot;cure&quot; is far
worse than the disease.  Clearly, such an approach will only exacerbate
the problem.

<p>

For example, the results of the National Survey of Adolescent
Males published in the November 1993 issue of <I>Public Health
Reports</I> show that young males who were taught about birth
control were more likely to experiment with sex at an earlier
age than if they had been taught nothing at all.

<p>

Furthermore, and more significantly, explicit sex education tears
down the natural inhibitions and defenses of both young boys and
girls, leaving them vulnerable to sexual predators.  Indeed, it
is a well-documented fact that pedophiles often use pornography
to lure their young victims.

<p>

That pedophiles attempt to wear down the defenses of the young
through pornography is bad enough, but this type of desensitizing
is now systematically taking place within schools through sex
education programs.  Unlike the sex education classes which parents
may remember, sex education today is explicit, graphic, and is
being taught in coed settings.  In fact, the Sex Information and
Education Council of the United States (SIECUS), a federally-funded,
nationally-recognized organization, has issued national sex education
guidelines which promote teaching kindergartners about masturbation
and junior and senior high school students about the &quot;benefits&quot;
of pornography, among other topics.

<p>

This current trend of adult men impregnating teenage girls is
a natural consequence of family breakdown and the sexualization
of children.  But what children need now -- and have always needed
-- is for adults to protect their innocence.  They need fathers
and mothers who will love and supervise them, laws that punish
statutory rapists, and school programs which do nothing to harm
the value, sanctity, and sacred mystery of sex.  Only then can
this tide be turned.  And if we are to survive as a society, it
must.

<p>
-- 5/8/96
<p>

<center>***</center>

<p>

<i>Gracie S. Hsu, M.H.S., is a policy analyst at the Family Research
Council, a Washington D.C.-based research and educational organization.</i>

<p>

<center>
<b>
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/perspective/">Other Perspectives</a>] 
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/policypapers.html">Other Policy Papers</a>]
[<a href="/townhall/FRC/reproduce/reproduc.html">Reproducing This 
Article</a>]
</b>

<p>
<hr size = 3>
